{"id":"1707.00692","submitter":"Alexandre Gallenne","authors":"A. Gallenne, P. Kervella, A. Merand, N. R. Evans and C. Proffitt","title":"Dynamical masses of Cepheids from the GAIA parallaxes","comments":"2 pages, 1 figure, proceedings of the conference \"Astrometry and\n  Astrophysics in the Gaia sky\" held in Nice, France, Apr. 24-28, 2017. arXiv\n  admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1707.00691","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/S1743921317006433","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The mass of a Cepheid is a fundamental parameter for studying the pulsation\nand evolution of intermediate-mass stars. But determining this variable has\nbeen a long-standing problem for decades. Detecting the companions (by\nspectroscopy or imaging) is a difficult task because of the brightness of the\nCepheids and the close orbit of the components. So most of the Cepheid masses\nare derived using stellar evolution or pulsation modeling, but they differ by\n10-20%. Measurements of dynamical masses offer the unique opportunity to make\nprogress in resolving this mass discrepancy. The first problem in studying\nbinary Cepheids is the high contrast between the components for wavelengths\nlonger than 0.5 {\\mu}m, which make them single-line spectroscopic binaries. In\naddition, the close orbit of the companions (< 40 mas) prevents us from\nspatially resolving the systems with a single-dish 8m-class telescope. A\ntechnique able to reach high spatial resolution and high- dynamic range is\nlong-baseline interferometry. We have started a long-term program that aims at\ndetecting, monitoring and characterizing physical parameters of the Cepheid\ncompanions. The GAIA parallaxes will enable us to combine interferometry with\nsingle-line velocities to provide unique dynamical mass measurements of\nCepheids.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Jul 2017 16:27:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-06-13"}
